x4freetext: -Differential cross section of the D(n,nnp)-reaction at
En = 13 MeV.
The EN-Tandem at Erlangen delivered a
1.5 microamp deuteron beam onto the deuterium target.
A deuterium gas target, 5 cm long and filled to
a pressure of 9 bar, was used to produce monoenergetic
neutrons of 13 MeV energy. The neutron beam was well
collimated with iron, water and paraffin in the zero-
degree direction.
A deuterated target scintillator was positioned
at a distance of 2.4 m from the gas cell. This target
enabled the determination of the proton energy and
gave a signal for the tof-measurement of the scattered
neutrons. The neutrons were detected with 22 identical
scintillators, placed at a distance of 70 cm. 18 of
these were located symmetrically at both sides of the
beam direction in the angular interval 17 - 110
degrees. 4 of the detectors were symmetrically posi-
tioned outside the scattering plane at a polar angle
of 50.5 degrees with respect to the beam direction.
Break-up events were defined by triple coinci-
dence between the target and one detector on each side
of the beam axis. With this set-up, kinematically com-
plete measurements could be performed.
The completely deuterated target scintillator,
NE232, had a diameter of 4 cm and a height of 8 cm.
The 22 neutron detectors, NE213, had a diameter of
5.3 cm and a height of 10.1 cm. All the detectors were
equipped with neutron-gamma pulse shape discrimina-
tion.
Elastic n-d scattering measure-
ments were performed simultaneously for an absolute
normalization of the differential break-up cross sec-
tion.
.Active, deuterated scintillation counter. See under
keyword DETECTOR.
.The data were corrected for background, neutron
attenuation and detection efficiency.
total error include:
counting statistics, 2 - 6%,
and uncertainty in background subtraction (< 2%)
The systematic error is mainly an uncertainty:
the scale uncertainty, which include the
corrections, 5%
the normalization to the elastic
n-D scattering, (<2%)
.Data obtained from J. Strate, March 6, 1989.
